1 _DSCR Oral/Written Family History
1 _META <metadataxml><content><line>&lt;p&gt;Jane Colvin, the mother of seven children, had an interesting background.&amp;nbsp; Her father Robert Colvin was a kind Christian, a Prebyterian in faith and a Democrat from Pennsylvania.&amp;nbsp; Known by hi
2 CONC s friends as &amp;quot;Uncle Bobby&amp;quot; he was German and was born in Pennsylvania in the year 1812. Robert came to Scotland County by covered wagon and entered government land and lived most of his life on a farm southwest of the community o
2 CONC f Kilwinni--northwest of Memphis.&amp;nbsp; Robert went to California during the &amp;quot;Gold Rush&amp;quot; in 1849 with a group of ox teams.&amp;nbsp; He was gone from home for two years and came back empty handed.&amp;nbsp; During the Civil Wa
2 CONC r Robert was a homeguard and was stationed in Memphis.&amp;nbsp; While away from home one day the Bushwackers took his prized horses and colts.&amp;nbsp; Elizabeth, his wife, begged them not to take a particular one which was a pet of the children.
2 CONC &amp;nbsp; One daughter Jane remembered the other children clinging to their Mother and all crying.&amp;nbsp; They not only took the horses but made them jump the bars used for a gate.&amp;nbsp; Robert and his family face many hardships but they re
2 CONC ared a family of two boys and five girls including Jane Colvin Lancaster.&amp;nbsp; They never accumulated much money but had the necessities and a strong faith in God.&amp;nbsp; Robert passed away after a lingering illness of kidney trouble in 189
2 CONC 8 and was buriedn in Pleasant Hill Cemetery.&amp;nbsp; Jane lancaster remained a widow till she passed away at the home of her daughters Lula Gutman Moore on June 6, 1945.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;!--[if gte ms
